	abstract = {Traditional methods of exam evaluation are often time-consuming, subjective, and prone to inconsistency and biases due to human participation. This research begins with a comparative study between different language models, highlighting the behavior and performance of different language models in evaluating short subjective answers. We compare both SLMs and LLMs, such as LLaMA, Gemma, Phi, and others, to see how effective they are in automating the grading process. After this comparative analysis, two additional experiments are performed to improve grading precision: the first is fine-tuning the GPT 3.5-Turbo model on domain-specific grading datasets to better match model predictions with human evaluators. The second experiment checks for RAG, where the GPT-4 model has access to external educational resources like subject-specific textbooks/reference books to enhance contextual understanding. The findings provide insight into the relative strengths of each strategy and blending generative AI with domain-specific enhancement for accurate, scalable, and equitable evaluation in education.  © 2025 Copyright held by the owner/author(s).},
