	abstract = {Generative Artificial Intelligence (Gen AI) is reshaping education by facilitating advances in adaptive and inclusive learning experiences. This study investigates the usage of Gen AI technologies among post-secondary students with disabilities (SWDs) and explores implications of this usage for supporting accessible and equitable learning design. It also examines students' perceptions of Gen AI tools in terms of perceived usefulness, ease of use, trust, satisfaction, and intention for continuous usage. A structured survey instrument, grounded in the Technology Acceptance Model (TAM) and in inclusive education frameworks, was developed and validated to capture learner experiences. The study employs a quantitative approach, utilizing stratified random sampling, to reach students with disabilities and provide a control sample. While data collection is ongoing, this paper presents the study design, conceptual framework, and research model. Preliminary insights highlight pedagogical, technological, and ethical determinants of Gen AI adoption and impact. Future work will present empirical results and recommendations to inform the continued development of practical and ethical Gen AI policy and practice in inclusive higher education. © 2026 IEEE.},
