	abstract = {This study examines the use of large language models for grading assignments in computer science education. A dataset of authentic student submissions, including source code, written documents, and image-based content, was evaluated using a controlled prompt strategy designed to enforce uniform numeric scoring. The models were assessed based on their ability to produce grades aligned with human evaluations while adhering to strict output constraints. The analysis focuses on grading accuracy, consistency, and sensitivity to task structure and prompt formulation. The results indicate that language models can support grading in structured assignments with clearly defined expectations, while their reliability decreases in open-ended or loosely specified tasks. Prompt formulation influenced output stability, particularly for incomplete or ambiguous submissions. Overall, the findings suggest that large language models can assist instructors in scaling assessment, provided they are deployed with clear procedures and human oversight to maintain fairness and alignment with educational objectives. © 2026, Budapest Tech Polytechnical Institution. All rights reserved.},
