	abstract = {The widespread adoption of large language models (LLMs) such as ChatGPT has transformed how students engage with learning tasks, often creating unregulated and instructorinvisible pathways to problem solving. This paper proposes a structured framework for computer-Aided instruction (CAI) grounded in cognitive apprenticeship, with instructors as the central evaluators of learning and LLMs as dynamic, scaffolded guides. We implement this model through a prompt-engineered Custom GPT that transitions between modeling and assessment phases, providing dialogic feedback and supporting reflective practice. Our framework incorporates prompt engineering techniques such as state priming, few-shot prompting, and negative prompting to align LLM behavior with educational goals. Preliminary observations suggest that while LLMs can improve formative feedback and engagement, their use must be carefully structured to avoid cognitive shortcuts and preserve instructional integrity. We conclude with practical design principles for integrating LLMs into teacher-guided assessment workflows. © 2025 IEEE.},
