	affiliations = {School of Education, Guangzhou University, Guangzhou, China},
	abstract = {With the rapid development of generative artificial intelligence, large language model (LLM) tools, such as ChatGPT, are increasingly integrated into higher education, significantly shaping how university students learn and interact with knowledge. This study focuses on undergraduates majoring in Educational Technology at Guangzhou University and employs a framework based on the Technology Acceptance Model (TAM). The model includes four key variables: perceived usefulness, perceived ease of use, perceived risk, and behavioral/cognitive factors. A mixed-methods approach, combining a structured questionnaire and thematic analysis, was used to examine the mechanisms influencing students' usage intentions and subjective experiences. Quantitative results indicate that behavioral and cognitive engagement, along with perceived usefulness, significantly and positively affect students' intention to use LLMs. This suggests that students with more experience are more likely to recognize the benefits of LLMs and continue using them. Perceived risk has a moderate negative influence, while perceived ease of use does not show a significant predictive effect. The qualitative analysis further reveals that students acknowledge the positive roles of LLMs in enhancing learning efficiency, supporting academic tasks, and expanding knowledge. However, they also express concerns about academic integrity, information reliability, technological dependence, and lack of emotional understanding. This study extends the theoretical application of the TAM in the context of educational AI tools and provides practical insights for guiding the responsible and effective implementation of LLMs in higher education. © 2025 IEEE.},
