	abstract = {With the advent of Artificial Intelligence (AI) and Machine Learning (ML), STEM faculty at higher education institutions need to design and develop a framework to incorporate and utilize AI/ML responsibly into the courses. With the development of new technology, there is a greater need to foster AI literacy amongst the students and faculty. Faculty must learn to use AI to advance student learning rather than pushing back against it. With each scientific development, there is an associated challenge but at the same time, there is greater opportunity to learn. There is a greater need to develop a thoughtful, learner-centered approach to integrating generative AI into the course curriculum and teaching practice. Strategies need to be brainstormed to use generative AI to support learners’ intellectual development and development of self-directed learners. The challenges that come with AI include academic integrity and honesty, ethics, resistance to change, and overreliance on technology. For the present research, AI is being used in curriculum development as well as creating assessments, projects, numerical problem sets, question banks for homework and group practice, pre-class and post-class quizzes, creation of problem sets with variations of knowns and unknown parameters, and activities to identify the gaps in prior knowledge, breaking down complex problems into a series of simplistic component tasks/skills, using AI to sift through common mistakes made during assessments to provide timely and actionable feedback, designing real-world application problems to connect the engineering concepts to real-world applications, and using AI to sift through the one-minute papers to identify the top grey areas and using the class time effectively to address the grey areas, provide feedback and answer questions. The results in terms of learning are being evaluated with the results due at the end of Fall 2025 and Spring 2026 semesters. © 2026, Begell House Inc. All ri