	abstract = {Generative AI is becoming a novel driver of entrepreneurship education by supporting ideation, business modeling, and assessment. However, little is known about its psychological mechanisms in shaping students' entrepreneurial pathways. Informed by the Stimulus-Organism-Response (SOR) framework, this research examined whether digital entrepreneurial self-efficacy mediates the relationship between GenAI-enhanced learning and digital entrepreneurial intention. Survey data were collected from 402 Chinese university students across the Yangtze River Delta who had prior experience with GenAI in entrepreneurship learning. Results showed that students' experience with GenAI in entrepreneurial learning significantly predicted digital entrepreneurial self-efficacy and intention, and that self-efficacy positively predicted digital entrepreneurial intention. Mediation analysis further confirmed that digital entrepreneurial self-efficacy partially mediated the relationship between GenAI-enhanced entrepreneurial learning and digital entrepreneurial intention. These findings clarify how GenAI-enhanced entrepreneurial learning fosters students' confidence for digital entrepreneurship, contributing to the application of the SOR framework and to the literature on technology-intensive entrepreneurship education.  © 2025 Copyright held by the owner/author(s).},
