	affiliations = {University of South Florida, Department of Computer Science and Engineering, Tampa, FL, United States},
	abstract = {This innovative practice WIP paper describes the challenges caused by use of AI tools in the classroom. Since the introduction of Artificial Intelligence (AI) tools (e.g., ChatGPT, Stable Diffusion, Meta Llama 3, Mistral AI, GPT-4o, etc.) [1] into academia, many students have openly embraced these tools to help them progress in their courses. This has prompted concerns from faculty regarding the maintenance of academic integrity. Despite these concerns, new AI tools continue to be developed, and students are rapidly outpacing faculty in their adoption and use of these tools [2]. This trend suggests that AI is not a passing phenomenon, particularly in educational settings. To understand how students can use AI tools to complete assignments, instructors must recognize how these tools can be misused. Computer Science instructors need to understand how assignments can be presented to AI tools and the types of responses these tools generate. This paper examines the ways students can use AI tools to produce responses that could be submitted as class assignments and compares these results to solutions generated by human authors or instructors. Additionally, the paper recommends strategies for creating assignments that are more likely to be solved by students than by AI tools. Using this knowledge, instructors can be more confident that assigned work will be completed by their students. © 2025 IEEE.},
