	affiliations = {University of Electronic Science and Technology of China, Sichuan, Chengdu, China},
	abstract = {This empirical study investigates the impact of AI-assisted teaching and learning on university students' academic performance. Data from 2000 students, including AI usage frequency (0-1 scale), scores in six diverse subjects, and overall GPA, were analyzed using correlation analysis. The study also examined AI usage distribution, compared AI integration support rates between 649 teachers and 1,712 students, and developed a Multi-Layer Perceptron (MLP) model to predict AI support scores with feature importance. Results show significant positive correlations between AI usage and academic performance (overall GPA r=0.289), with stronger associations in technical subjects (e.g., Microelectronic Devices r=0.312) than humanities (e.g., Modern History r=0.134). AI usage was found to be relatively uniformly distributed. Teachers (mean support=0.677) exhibited significantly higher support for AI integration than students (mean support=0.564). The findings suggest that AI tools can enhance academic outcomes, particularly in technical fields, but their subject-dependent impact necessitates tailored integration strategies in higher education. © 2025 Copyright held by the owner/author(s).},
