	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105037628032?origin=resultslist},
	affiliations = {Cit - University, Department of Information Technology, Cebu, Philippines},
	abstract = {Artificial intelligence (AI) continues to reshape employability training, particularly in preparing students for any job interviews. This study introduces InterviewAI, a voice-based web platform that simulates job interviews and evaluates spoken responses using a deterministic STAR + Core Competency scoring framework. The system separates the question generation and rule-based evaluation processes, ensuring fairness, traceability, and transparency. The quantitative evaluation involved 76 university students from various institutions who participated in mock interviews and completed post-use surveys assessing usability, fairness, and learning impact. Analysis revealed strong usability (M = 4.22, SD = 0.61) and fairness (M = 4.18, SD = 0.77), with an overall interview performance mean of 78.6 (SD = 8.1). Correlation results (r=0.34, p<0.01) showed that repeated practice improved structured interview performance. Findings confirm that InterviewAI enhances students' ability to organize responses using the STAR method, while fostering user trust through transparent evaluation logic. The deterministic scoring rubric consists of STAR Analysis (50%): Situation (0-25), Task (0-25), Action (0-25), Result (0-25) and Core Competencies (50%): Relevance (0-20), Clarity (0-15), Confidence (0-15). This proportional weighting was adapted from structured-interview research demonstrating that balanced attention to behavioral completeness and communication delivery yields more reliable and valid assessments of candidate performance [1]-[2] [4] [3]. Similar frameworks in interview-simulation studies and explainable-AI evaluations emphasize equal weighting between content structure and expressive competence to ensure fairness, transparency, and interpretability [5]-[7]. © 2026 IEEE.},
