	affiliations = {School of Computing Science Simon Fraser University, Surrey, BC, Canada; Department of Computing, East Tennessee State University, Johnson City, TN, United States; Department of Computing, Glasgow Caledonian University, Glasgow, United Kingdom; School of Computing University of Eastern Finland, Joensuu, Finland; Department of Computer Science, University of Exeter Exeter, Devon, United Kingdom; School of Computer and Mathematical Sciences, The University of Adelaide, Adelaide, Australia; Department of Computer and Robotics Education, University of Nigeria Nsukka, Enugu, Nigeria; Department of Curriculum Studies and Educational Technology, Usmanu Danfodiyo University, Sokoto, Sokoto, Nigeria},
	abstract = {Rapid development has generated a plethora of online content and technologies, including those for learning. As a result, an extensive range of tools, platforms, and content are available to support diverse student preferences. While offering potential, the effective use and development of these resources are hindered by multiple factors. First, these technologies are not available to the same degree to all learners around the world, and the availability often determines adoption. Second, when available, effective adoption is impeded by a host of influences such as differences in educator and student experiences. Third, the limited availability of studies to inform educator choices constrains effective adoption. We study learning technologies in computing science higher education to facilitate adoption for different groups of learners. We consider pedagogical content and learning management platforms (e.g. videos, open textbooks, practice exercises, and assistive tools leveraging Large Language Models); collaboration tools (e.g. shared notebooks, peer assessment); tools, languages and environments to support learning specific topics, including those that are useful for learners but may or may not be designed specifically for that purpose (e.g. Integrated Development Environments, GitHub); and tools to support learning of specific topics, that may be leveraged within pedagogical content (e.g. visualizations, simulations, libraries). We expand on our findings for diverse learners (e.g., different needs or access patterns) and emerging technologies (e.g., tutor robots, virtual and augmented reality, etc.) and possible strategies and best practices for effective adoption and class integration. © 2025 Copyright held by the owner/author(s).},
