	abstract = {This innovative practice full paper describes the effectiveness of self-hosted large language models (LLMs) for automatic grading of introductory programming (CS1) assignments using various rubrics. As computer science education (CSE) expands, the need for scalable grading solutions increases. Traditional grading is timeconsuming, and automated tools often lack meaningful feedback. LLM-based grading offers efficient assessment of large numbers of student submissions with adaptive feedback. However, remotely hosted systems like ChatGPT raise privacy concerns due to sharing sensitive student data externally. Self-hosted LLMs address privacy concerns by keeping data local. Earlier studies reported inconsistent grading with selfhosted models, raising concerns about reliability. This study reevaluates the accuracy of self-hosted models for CS1 assignment grading and examines how rubric design influences scoring consistency. The study used grading data from a semester-long CS1 course with 124 students and nine programming assignments. Initially, ten self-hosted LLMs were evaluated on their ability to assign scores on a 100-point scale without rubric guidance, establishing a baseline. Subsequently, the five best-performing models were assessed using five distinct rubrics: holistic 4-point, holistic 8 point, analytic 15-point, analytic 20-point, and a hybrid 100-point rubric that was used in the course. These rubrics varied in assessment granularity, facilitating analysis of LLM performance across different scoring frameworks. The analysis examined grading consistency and assessed how rubric structure impacted performance. Findings from this research provide insights into self-hosted LLMs reliability for automated grading, effectiveness of different rubric styles, and implications for integrating LLM-assisted grading into broader CSE practices. © 2025 IEEE.},
