	year = {2025},
	journal = {Proceedings of the ACM Great Lakes Symposium on VLSI, GLSVLSI},
	pages = {498 - 502},
	doi = {10.1145/3716368.3735218},
	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105017558772?origin=resultslist},
	affiliations = {University of Central Florida, Orlando, FL, United States},
	abstract = {The growth of educational data creates opportunities for innovative skill assessment technologies such as micro-credentialing frameworks, which involve tagging individual digitized quiz questions with specific skills to granularly track student progress over time. Our proposed approach combines the reasoning strengths of Generative AI (GenAI) to autonomously tag questions with the efficiency of non-parametric classification, leveraging a novel string classification system that employs the Gzip compression algorithm and Normalized Compression Distance (NCD) metric. Experimental results demonstrate a 58-fold speedup in classification time, achieving an optimal balance between accuracy and efficiency. We also evaluate the performance of different locally hostable Large Language Models (LLMs) on various devices, measuring their average latency to classify questions. Notably, three out of four tested LLMs demonstrated high agreement with a topic matter expert in classifying unseen quiz questions, validating their potential for accurate skills assessment. Furthermore, we investigate the optimal threshold for utilizing individual LLMs before switching to non-parametric classification, exploring different percentages of LLM usage to minimize latency while maintaining accuracy. Our findings show that by strategically combining LLMs with non-parametric classification, we can reduce classification time, making this hybrid approach a promising solution for scaling needs as the amount of questions grow among courses. © 2025 Copyright held by the owner/author(s). Publication rights licensed to ACM.},
