	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105040101354?origin=resultslist},
	affiliations = {Changchun University of Architecture and Civil Engineering, Jilin, Changchun, China},
	abstract = {The rapid advancement of generative artificial intelligence presents unprecedented opportunities for pedagogical innovation in ideological and political theory courses at higher education institutions, while simultaneously posing significant challenges to ideological security and educational ethics of such curricula. This study employs a Transformer-based AIGC model (GPT-4 variant) for dynamic content generation and a knowledge-graph-enhanced recommendation system for personalized learning pathways. This study aims to systematically explore viable pathways for leveraging AIGC to enhance ideological and political education, while delineating ethical boundaries for its application, thereby establishing a secure and effective new model of "Intelligence + Ideological Education."A combined methodology of literature review, theoretical analysis, and computational experiments is employed. First, it analyzes the logical foundations and inherent tensions in integrating AIGC with ideological education at the theoretical level. Second, it constructs specific application models across two dimensions: algorithm-driven content generation and data-driven personalized teaching. Finally, it systematically identifies potential ethical risks across four dimensions - values, agency, data, and cognition - and proposes a collaborative governance framework. Experimental results indicate that the AIGC model achieved a content relevance score of 4.7±0.5, while the recommendation system improved student engagement by 75%. The research indicates that AIGC can significantly enhance the richness of ideological and political teaching resources, the impact of teaching scenarios, and the targeted nature of learning pathways. However, four boundaries must be strictly upheld: the red line of ideological security, the baseline of educational autonomy, the defense line of data privacy protection, and the warning line of academic integrity. The tool-like nature of technology must not usurp the value-driven leadership role of educators. To advance the deep integration of AIGC into ideological and political courses, we must establish the principle of "student-centered education, value-driven guidance, and compliance-based boundaries."This requires building a collaborative governance system characterized by national standards, institution-specific protocols, teacher leadership, and technology for good, ensuring technological innovation consistently serves the fundamental mission of fostering virtue and cultivating talent.  © 2026 Copyright held by the owner/author(s).},
	author_keywords = {AIGC; algorithmic fairness; educational ethics; generative artificial intelligence; human-AI collaboration; ideological and political theory courses; personalized teaching; recommendation systems; technology governance transformer architecture},
