	doi = {10.1109/FIE63693.2025.11328437},
	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105033033701?origin=resultslist},
	affiliations = {Auburn University, Auburn, AL, United States},
	abstract = {This research innovative practice full paper explores the use of software engineering principles as a guide to systematically improving the quality of concept maps. Concept maps are promoted as an effective tool for students and instructors to visualize relationships among key concepts. A 'good' concept map is one that stands alone and does not require instructor explanation. Just as software can possess 'smells' that affect postproduction understandability, so can concept maps. This paper evaluates the quality of concept maps through the lens of software development to identify and address potential 'smells' in maps, such as irrelevant concepts, missing concepts, duplicated concepts, ordered concepts, weak relationships, incomplete relationships, inconsistent levels of detail, and misuse of crosslinks. This research was motivated by discovering elements that led to confusion, ambiguity, and misunderstanding in instructor-authored concept maps. The effectiveness of the approach was evaluated by employing generative artificial intelligence tools to compare maps containing smells with maps with smells removed. This paper provides insights into how software engineering principles can enhance the design and assessment of educational concept maps, fostering critical thinking and ultimately improving both students' and instructors' understanding, retention, and application of complex knowledge. It lays the foundation for concept maps that can be digested by generative AI tools, thus possibly opening them to automated critique. © 2025 IEEE.},
