	abstract = {This work in progress, innovative practice paper reports on a study of Large Language Models (LLM) in providing assessments for a Software Quality Assurance (SQA) project. LLMs are sophisticated architectures trained on extensive text corpora, utilizing intuitive training methods that enhance their ability to understand, analyze, and generate natural language text. Thus, LLMs can be leveraged to assist and assess complex assignments within the academic classroom. This study examines the capabilities of LLMs, three in particular: ChatGPT 4o, Claude 2, and the new DeepSeek R1, and their efficacy in evaluating a SQA project. While the capabilities of LLMs in evaluating code are relatively understood, subjective projects are still relatively unknown. SQA is an inherently subjective practice, making it a valuable framework for assessing LLMs' ability to evaluate projects involving subjective elements. The LLM will generate an assessment following the rubric. The SQA-educator and course grader will independently evaluate all students (n=20), enabling comparative analysis of rubric category alignment between the LLM's outputs and human assessors' evaluations. © 2025 IEEE.},
