	affiliations = {Politehnica University of Bucharest, Department of Computer Science, Bucharest, Romania; Universitat Politécnica de Valéncia, Valéncia, Spain},
	abstract = {This paper presents the design and implementation of EduStack, a full-stack educational application tailored to the management of academic projects in higher education. Developed in response to widespread feedback from students and instructors, the platform addresses critical shortcomings in existing educational systems-such as Moodle, Google Class-room, and Microsoft Teams-by offering a role-customizable digital workspace that supports structured project development, transparent evaluation, and continuous feedback. A comparative analysis of these platforms highlighted significant limitations in adapting to project-based workflows, including poor progress tracking, inflexible user interfaces, and insufficient granularity in assessment. To address these gaps, EduStack was built with a modular architecture using Angular, Flask, and MongoDB. Core features include section-based project segmentation, auto-saving mechanisms, grading rubrics, real-time notifications, ranking dashboards, and dynamically configurable evaluation criteria. A key innovation of the platform is the integration of a Large Language Model (LLM)-driven grading assistant, which analyzes student project content to generate automated grade suggestions aligned with predefined rubrics. This AI-powered feature enhances assessment consistency and reduces instructor work-load. Preliminary evaluations of the LLM component indicate promising performance, with future opportunities identified for domain-specific fine-tuning and integration of custom machine learning pipelines. The platform demonstrates that combining user-centered design with emerging AI technologies such as LLMs can yield scalable, intelligent solutions that align with the evolving demands of modern academic environments. © 2025 IEEE.},
