	affiliations = {Aberdeen Institute of Data Science and Artificial Intelligence, South China Normal University, Guangdong, Guangzhou, China},
	abstract = {Education technologies often have difficulties balancing semantic flexibility and precise descriptions. The former characteristic is related to how well the technology understands the students' different response forms. The latter is a necessary part of domain-specific knowledge assessment. In this study, we introduce EduGraph, an innovatively combined bidirectional framework. It can find the abstract relationships between large language models (LLMs) and knowledge graphs in education. It also establishes an ongoing cognitive link between statistical language processing and symbolic knowledge representation. In this way, it breaks the limitations of other approaches. This framework instead forms an enhanced system that can perform both educational reasoning and assessment. Our approach contributes in three ways. Our assessment framework has two layers. Firstly, it connects the evaluation of semantic similarity to the confirmation of key concepts. This improves the system's complex explanation ability. Besides, it has a dynamic knowledge expansion mechanism. This can automatically update the curriculum by adding semantic relationships. Apart from that, our framework includes a student progress tracking system. This system keeps track of students' learning achievements and finds knowledge gaps. Using human evaluation as the standard, our framework shows better performance than the traditional or single-modality AI approaches in assessment accuracy (89.1% F1 score). The combined system can evaluate student responses more precisely and can better deliver adaptive educational experiences. © 2025 Copyright held by the owner/author(s).},
