	abstract = {Generative AI, and particularly AI coding tools, have been adopted both by industry and by students in record time, transforming the computer science landscape and raising multiple challenges in undergraduate CS education, both in terms of assessment integrity, code instruction and the potential for tools to replace coders. Tools like ChatGPT, Copilot, and others are now embedded into students’ workflows—offering instant answers, code suggestions, debugging help, and even detailed conceptual explanations [1, 3]. As a result, the computing curriculum and the role of CS educators are shifting in real time in our classrooms and labs. Office hours are less attended. Teaching assistants report fewer questions. Course discussion forums that once facilitated many technical conversation are now unusually quiet. The classic student queries—“How do I fix this bug?”, “What’s the difference between pass by value and pass by reference?”—are no longer being directed at us. They are being asked, and often answered quite well, by AI tools. Coding practice is also changing as the tools can produce, explain and even test small programs. Foundational knowledge is evolving as a result. © 2025 Copyright held by the owner/author(s).},
