	pages = {},
	doi = {10.1109/FIE63693.2025.11328663},
	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105032992231?origin=resultslist},
	affiliations = {Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University, Department of Electrical Engineering and Computer Science, FL, United States},
	abstract = {This innovative practice full paper describes a novel method to leverage Large Language Models (LLMs) to update course content and address student feedback to improve their learning experience. One major indicator of a professor's effectiveness is how prepared students feel regarding the subject matter after completing the class. There are two main reasons why students might feel unprepared: either the content was inadequate, or the professor's delivery of the material was unclear. Students' feedback is typically collected through course evaluations conducted at the end of the semester. In these evaluations, the students assess, through a series of multiple choice and short answer questions, the course content, the professor's performance, and provide suggestions for improving the learning experience. Implementing changes based on these suggestions is essential to maintaining highquality teaching and improving the student experience. However, this process can be labor-intensive and timeconsuming, sometimes causing professors to neglect class updates. In recent years, LLMs have gained widespread acceptance and are being utilized for various tasks in education, from teaching correct coding practices to software requirements tracing. This work presents a case study in the Department of Electrical Engineering and Computer Science at Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University that expands LLM education usage by utilizing them to assist professors in addressing student comments from course evaluations. LLMs can help professors quickly compile course evaluations and identify areas of improvement. Furthermore, this work explores the usage of LLMs to find evidence of department-wide directives, e.g., specific utilization of techniques or content, to streamline analysis of course content. This can be particularly beneficial for department-wide initiatives, e.g., ABET (formerly the Accreditation Board for Engineering and Technology, Inc.) or teaching improvements. The method proposed in this paper offers a solution to help faculty improve their courses based on student evaluations and department initiatives while alleviating some of the time pressure of doing so. © 2025 IEEE.},
	author_keywords = {Course Assessment; Department-wide Initiatives; Higher Education; Large Language Models; Student Course Evaluations; Student Experience},
