	doi = {10.1109/ICEIDT66693.2025.11473581},
	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105037399749?origin=resultslist},
	affiliations = {Southeast University, Department of Electrical & Electronic Engineering, Dhaka, Bangladesh},
	abstract = {In this paper, the impression of Artificial Intelligence (AI) as applied to the academic development of engineering students at the private universities in Bangladesh is reported. The study tried to identify trends in the adoption of AI, perceptions of benefits and limitations, and institutional preparedness. The sample consisted of 300 students. The given results have shown that 72.3% of engineering students use AI tools, with ChatGPT being the most popular (100% of AI users), followed by GitHub (23.5%), Grammarly (16.1%), Copilot (23.5%), MATLAB AI (7.4%), Wolfram Alpha (4.1%), and Symbolab (3.2%). Most AI users utilize AI to write, complete homework, and conduct research. The study reveals that almost 83% of users use AI on a daily or weekly basis. Approximately 55 percent of AI users report that AI has helped them improve their studies, and 72.3% of respondents report that AI saves them time. However, only 43.7% of respondents think that the use of AI has a positive impact on learning, while 56.3% of them respond that it has no significant impact on learning. The difference in discipline can also be seen when Computer Science and Engineering students prove to be the top AI users (99.1%), followed by Electrical and Electronic Engineering students (79.3%), Mechanical and Civil Engineering students (36.5% and 37%). In response to having institutional policies and awareness, the reply from 83.3% of respondents is negative, which represents the lack of awareness of the universities in Bangladesh, and 10.7% respond positively. By addressing the impressions, benefits, and academic usages of AI adoption, this study contributes to a deeper understanding of how AI can be leveraged to support academic growth while encouraging sustainable and equitable adoption in the context of resource-constrained higher education systems. © 2025 IEEE.},
	author_keywords = {AI adoption in engineering education; AI tools and academic integrity; digital divide in higher education in Bangladesh; institutional preparedness; student perceptions of AI learning impact},
	keywords = {Artificial intelligence; Education computing; Students; Academic integrity; Artificial intelligence adoption in engineering education; Artificial intelligence learning; Artificial intelligence tool and academic integrity; Artificial intelligence tools; Bangladesh; Digital divide; Digital divide in high education in bangladesh; High educations; Institutional preparedness; Student perception of artificial intelligence learning impact; Student perceptions; Engineering education},
