	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105033214589?origin=resultslist},
	affiliations = {Queen Mary University of London, Faculty of Science and Engineering, London, United Kingdom},
	abstract = {Generative AI (GenAI) tools are becoming an increasingly integral part of Higher Education, yet many teaching approaches fail to address how to use them critically and responsibly. To bridge this gap, we implemented GenAI-based mini-projects in a second-year programming module for two separate Transnational Education (TNE) programmes involving over 750 students. Students were tasked with developing Java applications, solving real-world problems, such as a mathematics learning tool for Key Stage 2 and Key Stage 3 learners. They were required to design user-friendly graphical user interfaces (GUIs) to enable self-learning of the concepts of geometric shapes and attributes such as area, angles, and compound shapes. While students were encouraged to use GenAI, they were also required to submit their prompts, provide a reflective rationale, and demonstrate programming understanding. The project was assessed through a report, code submission, and an in-person viva. GenAI-based mini-projects enhanced students' critical thinking, problem-solving, and programming understanding through structured activities like prompt justification and viva sessions. While most students found GenAI helpful, its impact varied based on individual readiness and responsible use. Clear guidance and support in the TNE context led to consistent engagement and reduced mark review requests, indicating improved satisfaction and clarity in learning. A survey at the end of the module aims to assess the impact of the initiative and provide insights to guide the future integration of GenAI into computing education through practical, hands-on learning experiences. © 2025 IEEE.},
	author_keywords = {Computing Education; Generative AI; Higher Education; Java Programming; Undergraduate},
