	abstract = {This Work-in-Progress innovative practice paper investigates the integration of generative AI tutors into an undergraduate Operating Systems course to support student learning of complex topics such as CPU scheduling, memory management, and synchronization. The AI tutors, deployed through GitHub Codespaces and Microsoft Teams, leverage Socratic questioning, analogical reasoning, and iterative debugging to provide individualized, just-in-time guidance. Anchored in constructivist learning theory and prior work on AI-enhanced instruction, this approach targets the persistent challenge of student comprehension in systems-level content. Preliminary results from 24 participants suggest increased engagement, enhanced conceptual understanding, and more exploratory problem-solving behaviors. Data sources include AI usage logs, reflective journals, conceptual assessments, and a structured survey approved by the institutional review board. Early findings indicate that generative AI tools, when carefully designed and pedagogically aligned, can scaffold abstract content, promote self-regulated learning, and complement traditional instructional strategies. Ongoing work aims to optimize tutor prompt design, evaluate long-term learning gains, and explore the transferability of this approach to other technical domains. © 2025 IEEE.},
