	affiliations = {Northern Border University, College of Humanities and Social Sciences, Department of Languages and Translation, Arar, Saudi Arabia},
	abstract = {Addressing a developing yet mostly uncharted field of educational technology, this paper examines the present status of AI in higher education's automated curriculum creation. ML is becoming more popular in the field of education, but there is a dearth of studies specifically examining its impact on the creation of courses at the university level. The uses of advanced algorithms like TF-IDF for academic feature extraction and data pretreatment approaches in general have received very less research focus. it filled this knowledge vacuum by reviewing the literature extensively and then using network analysis to identify trends and recurrent themes in curriculum design using ML. Our new WSA-CNBiRN model, which is based on a quantum water strider algorithm, is designed to improve the automation of curriculum production and is based on these discoveries. In order to properly define and categorise different kinds of educational activities, this model was developed. The WSA-CNBiRN method demonstrated encouraging results in experimental assessments, reaching a high performance accuracy of 96.44%. These results highlight the AI's ability to revolutionize higher education's curriculum development and highlight the need for ongoing study in this dynamic field to back scalable, data-driven instructional design.  © 2025 IEEE.},
