	affiliations = {FH Dortmund, Department of Computer Science, Dortmund, Germany},
	abstract = {Statistical data analysis has become a fundamental skill across all disciplines, including computer science. However, students outside traditional statistics programs often lack structured guidance in applying statistical reasoning to real-world problems. We present an interactive, browser-based learning tool in which data analysis skills are practiced in an accessible and hands-on way. The tool was developed to support computer science and other technically oriented students who have little prior exposure to applied statistics. It combines individualized dataset generation with step-by-step guidance and a conversational chatbot interface powered by a large language model. Learners work independently on realistic case studies provided by a simulated client, enabling authentic engagement while minimizing the risk of plagiarism. Analytical methods and visualizations can be selected through a simple interface, and results are immediately displayed and stored for reporting. By integrating feedback and natural-language interaction, the tool facilitates self-directed learning while abstracting away technical barriers. Formal grading remains with instructors, ensuring compliance with ethical and legal standards, such as the EU AI Act. The system aims to enhance statistics education across disciplines by combining automation, fairness, and usability in a unified learning framework.  © 2025 IEEE.},
