	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105033005753?origin=resultslist},
	affiliations = {Tsinghua University, Dept. of Computer Science and Technology, Bejing, China},
	abstract = {This work in progress innovative practice paper investigates the capabilities of GPT applications, specifically ChatGPT, ChatGLM, and ERNIE, in generating code for introductory-level algorithm problems. The rapid development of GPT technology has sparked interest in its potential to assist teachers and students in various educational tasks. Although ChatGPT achieves high accuracy in exercises on basic programming concepts and syntaxes, its performance is not as impressive in more advanced programming tasks. This work employed a comprehensive test set of 50 algorithm problems, covering various categories like Recursion, Dynamic Programming, and Simulation. Each problem included a detailed description, input/output specifications, and sample data. The GPT applications were tasked with generating C++ code solutions for each problem, and the code was evaluated based on its accuracy in processing test data and its runtime efficiency. The number of interactions required to correct errors in the generated code was also examined. The preliminary results indicated that GPT applications could achieve an average accuracy rate of over 50% after multiple rounds of interaction. ChatGLM demonstrated the highest accuracy rate among the tested applications. However, the accuracy rate varied across different problem categories, and problems of Dynamic Programming and Enumeration categories required more rounds of feedback and correction. The average runtime of generated code for Recursion and Dynamic Programming categories changed significantly with the increase of accuracy rate. The results suggest the need for educators to adapt assessment methods to account for the use of AI tools and mitigate potential over-reliance on AI assistance. © 2025 IEEE.},
	author_keywords = {assessment; educational software; first year curriculum},
	keywords = {BASIC (programming language); Codes (symbols); Curricula; Data handling; Dynamic programming; Engineering education; Software testing; Teaching; Accuracy rate; Assessment; Educational software; First-year curriculum; High-accuracy; Innovative practices; Level algorithms; Programming concepts; Recursions; Teachers'; C++ (programming language)},
