	year = {2025},
	journal = {TALE 2025 - 2025 IEEE International Conference on Teaching, Assessment, and Learning for Engineering, Proceedings},
	pages = {},
	doi = {10.1109/TALE66047.2025.11346784},
	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105033240700?origin=resultslist},
	affiliations = {Auckland University of Technology, Computer and Information Sciences Department, Auckland, New Zealand; Auckland University of Technology, Data Science and Artificial Intelligence Department, Auckland, New Zealand},
	abstract = {This paper presents the Snake Quiz Game, an interactive, browser-based assessment tool that reimagines multiple-choice quizzes as a fast-paced, game-based learning experience. Designed to foster active learning and real-time cognitive recall, the game compels students to physically steer a snake avatar toward the correct answer within a limited time, making it difficult to pause, consult external tools, or engage in academic dishonesty, an increasingly urgent concern in the era of generative AI. Unlike static quiz formats, the Snake Quiz Game integrates motion, urgency, and competition to heighten focus and motivation. Features such as instant feedback, a live leaderboard, and an "Explain This Question"button support metacognitive development and sustained engagement. The game is deliberately simple to deploy, requires no login or installation, and is fully adaptable across disciplines and educational levels. Piloted in a first-year first-week programming course with over 500 students, the game so far attracted 218 unique players who logged 3,828 sessions across seven active days. More than half of the players (57.8%) returned repeatedly, with top scorers playing over 100 times and accumulating over 7 hours of voluntary engagement. The highest score-per-minute reached 10.6, illustrating both speed and mastery. These analytics underscore the game's potential as an AI-resistant, addictive, and educationally effective platform for formative assessment. A live demo is available at: https://ecms.nz/snake. © 2025 IEEE.},
	author_keywords = {AI-resistant assessment; digital integrity; educational technology; Game-based learning; multiple choice; student engagement},
	keywords = {Artificial intelligence; Curricula; E-learning; Education computing; Engineering education; Human computer interaction; Interactive computer graphics; Students; Active Learning; AI-resistant assessment; Assessment tool; Browser-based assessments; Digital integrity; Game-based Learning; Learning experiences; Learning time; Multiple choice; Student engagement; Educational technology},
