	affiliations = {School of Civil and Mechanical Engineering, Curtin University, Department of Mechanical Engineering, Bentley, WA, Australia; School of Civil and Mechanical Engineering, Curtin University, Department of Mechanical Engineering, Perth Campus, WA, United States},
	abstract = {This research-to-practice full paper aims to validate the hypothesis that the errorless and scaffolded pedagogies integrated to GAI and embedded in a Virtual Learning Environment (VLE) would produce a more effective learning outcome than the either one in isolation. As best evidence grounded studies on whether Generative Artificial Intelligence (GAI) supported learning is effective, ineffective, or alike the traditional learning are not available in the Teaching and Learning (T&L) literature, errorless and scaffolding learning methodologies were systematically integrated with GAI in a VLE for testing the hypothesis. Realizing that learning complex methods and concepts, embedded in STEM subjects can be challenging for high school students, domain of this work was introduction of geometry and trigonometry. The presented work demonstrates how to exploit the Large Language Models (LLMs) for implementing errorless and scaffolding learning methodologies in a GAI-supported T&L application. As such, this paper addresses the current gap in development and practical application of AI-driven VLEs' and educational tools. The interactive VLE was further augmented by the state-of-theart, multimedia cues. For validating the overall system, student post-learning feedback was sought. The system was also assessed and validated using the T&L Impact Assessment Tool (TALIAT), achieving a score of 88 / 160. This work demonstrates development of a hybrid static-dynamic architecture and using a dynamic content generation schema with transparent decision-making processes. Furthermore, this work defines a reproducible framework for integrating the latest AI technologies with proven pedagogical strategies, offering valuable insights for future AI-driven developments in educational domains. © 2025 IEEE.},
	author_keywords = {errorless learning; Generative AI; Large Language Models; learning theory; scaffolding learning; virtual learning environment},
	keywords = {Artificial intelligence; Computation theory; Computer aided instruction; E-learning; Engineering education; Federated learning; Learning systems; Scaffolds; Students; Teaching; Virtual reality; Effective Learning Outcomes; Errorless learning; Generative AI; Language model; Large language model; Learning Theory; Scaffolding learning; Supported learning; Teaching and learning; Virtual learning environments; Decision making},
