	affiliations = {Karpagam Academy of Higher Education, Department of Computer Science and Engineering, Coimbatore, India},
	abstract = {This paper introduces an alternative approach to the long-standing difficulties faced in conventional academic grading, particularly for descriptive and open-ended student responses. Traditional evaluation practices, although widely used, are often criticized for being time-consuming, inconsistent across evaluators, and increasingly impractical in classrooms with large student numbers. To overcome these challenges, the proposed framework integrates Optical Character Recognition (OCR) for digitizing handwritten content with the contextual reasoning ability of Large Language Models (LLMs). OCR technology is applied to convert written answers into editable digital form, while the LLM interprets meaning, evaluates correctness, and generates structured feedback aligned with reference rubrics. This dual-layer strategy is designed to improve efficiency, reduce subjectivity, and provide learners with more immediate and constructive feedback. Beyond system design, the paper also examines the effectiveness of the approach by considering the reliability of OCR across varied handwriting styles and the ability of LLMs to produce grading results comparable to human teachers. At the same time, the study highlights essential concerns such as algorithmic bias, data security, and the necessity of maintaining human oversight to preserve academic fairness and accountability. By balancing the benefits of automation with the irreplaceable role of educators, the proposed solution is positioned not as a substitute for teachers but as a supportive tool that can streamline evaluation, reduce workload, and enhance the quality of learning outcomes. © 2025 IEEE.},
