	abstract = {Multimodal generative artificial intelligence has also introduced real time multilingual translation, context aware conversational agents and extremely natural synthesizing voices as the immediate side effects of the blistering evolution of multimodal artificial intelligence, therefore creating a wholesome revolution in the field of speech technology. However, the growth of these features has also increased the possibility of bias, abuse, and spreading deep fakes, which is why greater clarity and responsibility are greatly needed.To address these issues, this manuscript presents the Hybrid Multimodal Speech Accountability Framework (HMSAF), a unique system architecture through which adversarial resilience, traceable multilingual resilient watermarking, and multilingual voice anonymisation are combined in a single system. HMSAF uses cross linguistic explainable AI (XAI) visualisations as well as twelve language independent privacy layer that includes code switched utterances and multimodal language models (MLLMs) that deliver coherent audio, textual, and visual embeddings to facilitate interpretability. Empirical assessments performed on ASVspoof2025, VoicePrivacy2024 and recently available MultiModal Provenance Bench (MMP Bench), have shown that HMSAF is persistent in overcoming baseline generative speech systems, and has achieved state of the-art detection resistance, lower watermark removal rates, as well as higher user trust scores. The suggested architecture ensures authenticity that is verifiable, with no reduction of the audio quality, so that the application of generative speech AI in sensitive fields like the media, education, and medicine can be implemented safely, transparently, effectively, and inclusively. © 2025 IEEE.},
