	affiliations = {University of Tartu, Institute of Computer Science, Tartu, Estonia; University of Tartu, Institute of Education, Tartu, Estonia},
	abstract = {Despite the increasing relevance of programming skills for future careers, informatics courses remain non-compulsory in Estonian schools. This paper presents the emergence, evolution, and key learnings from an introductory Python programming course designed to do more with less: providing hands-on programming experience and a broader introduction to the IT industry within just 105 academic hours, targeting a non-technical upper-secondary school with a language immersion focus. The course combines individual and project-based Python programming language learning, elements of digital product development and project management, and serves as career guidance for students considering further studies in IT. This study analyzes five years of the intervention using Action Research (AR) methodology, with student feedback collected during the fourth iteration using a survey based on the Learning Object Evaluation Scale for Students (LOES-S). Course design elements, including the digital learning environment (Discord, Notion, Lahendus), teaching methods (analogies, pop culture references, real-life-inspired homework, incremental learning), and course events (guest lessons, movie sessions, university and company visits), are examined in detail. Additionally, the challenges and adjustments required for grading programming homework assignments in the ChatGPT era are reflected upon. Course materials have been made publicly available to support fellow teachers and researchers interested in introducing similar interventions in their institutions. © 2025 IEEE.},
