	affiliations = {Dayananda Sagar University, Dept. Computer Science and Technology, Karnataka, Bengaluru, 560068, India},
	abstract = {Accurately grading student-created diagrams, such as flowcharts, remains a core challenge in STEM education because automated tools must evaluate both structural correctness and logical coherence. Conventional approaches based on text-matching heuristics, OCR pipelines, or large language models often miss the nuanced dependencies that link diagram components and can penalize valid alternative representations. To overcome these limitations, graph-based frameworks transform diagram elements into knowledge graphs, enabling more rigorous verification of logical relationships and revealing inconsistencies that text-only methods overlook. Reinforcement learning strategies further enhance assessment by continuously fine-tuning evaluation criteria through reward-driven feedback loops. By combining graph analytics, adaptive learning, and knowledge distillation, hybrid systems promise greater scalability, higher grading precision, and richer feedback for students. This review maps the evolution of diagram assessment techniques from heuristic and LLM-powered grading to graph-driven and reinforcement learning models and highlights future research directions for building more robust and scalable automated grading frameworks in STEM education.  © 2025 IEEE.},
